"A recent Brussels summit – involving the leaders of all 28 EU member states – saw data protection law climb to an unusually high level of attention. UK Prime Minister David Cameron made a personal last-ditch attempt to delay a tough new pan-European privacy law with the mantra “not before 2015”, according to an EU official who was present. Despite UK resistance, a new pumped-up pan-European data protection law is soon to be agreed. Yet there's disagreement about whether the law means more or less red tape. It's also unclear what exactly organisations need to do to about the new rules. But there's general agreement that UK firms need to start preparing now for the reforms, explains Tim Ring."
